aws::graph::propositions: # Boeing E75 Aircraft Accident Information
The accident involved a Boeing E75 aircraft.
The defining event was loss of lift during initial climb.
The aircraft experienced loss of control in flight during initial climb.
The aircraft collided with terrain or an object (non-CFIT) during initial climb.
The pilot was a 61-year-old male.
The pilot held a Private certificate.
The pilot had airplane rating for single-engine land.
The pilot had glider rating.
The pilot had no instrument rating.
The pilot had no instructor rating.
The pilot had a Class 3 medical certification with waivers/limitations.
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot had accumulated 1780 total flight hours in all aircraft.
The pilot had accumulated 611 flight hours in this make and model.
The aircraft was a Boeing E75.
The aircraft registration was N5176N.
The aircraft model/series was E75.
The aircraft category was Airplane.
The aircraft had an Aerobatic airworthiness certificate.
The aircraft serial number was 75-5379.
The aircraft had a tailwheel landing gear type.
The aircraft had 2 seats.
The aircraft had 1 reciprocating engine.
The engine manufacturer was LYCOMING.
The engine model/series was R680.
The engine was rated at 215 Horsepower.
The aircraft had an Emergency Locator Transmitter (ELT) installed but not activated.
The registered owner was on file.
The operator was on file.
The operator held no operating certificates.
